## Implementation Plan

### Problem
Homebrew post-install errors on macOS:
1. SQLiteError: unable to open database file (SQLITE_CANTOPEN) — from user 'bete'
2. Warning: read-only database + EPERM on zsh completions — from user 'am'

Root cause: `sudo brew install` creates root-owned ~/.sentry/ and
~/.local/share/zsh/ files. The setup command had no error handling, so any
failure aborted the entire post-install script.

The ongoing 'attempt to write a readonly database' errors in Sentry telemetry
(8 issues, 19 events, 100% macOS) are caused by the same root: root-owned
~/.sentry/cli.db from a previous sudo install.

### Investigation
- Confirmed macOS TCC does NOT restrict ~/.sentry/ — these are Unix
  permission errors, not sandbox denials
- All 19 Sentry readonly DB events are macOS 26.2 (Tahoe) — explained by
  macOS being the dominant platform + sudo brew being common there
- Moving the config dir would not help — the same permission issues would
  occur at any path if created by root

### Fixes

#### 1. Non-fatal setup steps (setup.ts)
Added bestEffort() wrapper that catches errors from each setup step and
logs a warning instead of crashing. Applies to: setInstallInfo(),
handlePathModification(), handleCompletions(), handleAgentSkills().

#### 2. Root-owned file detection in tryRepairReadonly (telemetry.ts)
Before attempting chmod (which fails on root-owned files), check statSync().uid.
If the file is owned by root (uid 0), emit a targeted message:
  'sudo chown -R <username> ~/.sentry'  or  'sudo sentry cli fix'
Username inferred from SUDO_USER > USER > USERNAME > os.userInfo().username.

#### 3. Ownership repair in sentry cli fix (fix.ts)
- checkOwnership() stats config dir + DB + WAL + SHM, returns files owned
  by a different uid than the current process
- handleOwnershipIssues() orchestrates:
  - Runs FIRST, before permissions (chmod fails on root-owned files)
  - Not root: prints sudo chown / sudo sentry cli fix instructions, exit 1
  - Running as root (sudo sentry cli fix): calls resolveUid(username) via
    'id -u <username>', then chown(path, targetUid, -1) on each file
- safeHandleSchemaIssues() extracted to keep func complexity in check
- Help text updated to document 'sudo sentry cli fix'
